com.yahoo.bullet.common

Class Validator

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.yahoo.bullet.common.Validator

  • public class Validator
extends Object
    This class validates instances of BulletConfig. Use Validator.Entry to define fields and Validator.Relationship to define relationships between them. It also provides a bunch of useful Predicate and BiPredicate for use in the checks for the entries and relationships and type converting Function for converting types of entries.

      • define

        public Validator.Entry define(String key)
        Creates an instance of the Entry using the name of the field. This field by default will pass the Predicate unless you add a check using Validator.Entry.checkIf(Predicate).
        Parameters:
        key - The name of the field.
        Returns:
        The created Validator.Entry.

      • relate

        public Validator.Relationship relate(String description,
                                     String keyA,
                                     String keyB)
        Create a relationship with a description for it for the given fields. By default, the relationship will hold true unless you provide a custom check using Validator.Relationship.checkIf(BiPredicate). By default, if the relationship fails to hold, the defaults defined by the Entries for these fields will be used unless you provide new ones using Validator.Relationship.orElseUse(Object, Object).
        Parameters:
        description - A string description of this relationship.
        keyA - The first field in the relationship.
        keyB - The second field in the relationship.
        Returns:
        The created Validator.Relationship.

      • evaluate

        public Validator.State evaluate(String description,
                                String... keys)
        Create a state with a description for the given fields. This lets you validate values for as many fields as you want. By default, the state check will hold true unless you provide one with Validator.State.checkIf(Predicate), which provides you the values for the fields you are defining this for. Unless you ask the the check to fail with Validator.State.orFail(), it will use the defaults for each of the entries.
        Parameters:
        description - A string description for this state validation.
        keys - The non-null fields for this state validation. They must already be defined as entries.
        Returns:
        The create Validator.State.

      • validate

        public void validate(BulletConfig config)
        Validate and normalize the provided BulletConfig for the defined entries and relationships. Then entries are used to validate the config first.
        Parameters:
        config - The config containing fields to validate.

      • copy

        public Validator copy()
        Returns a copy of this validator. Note that your various functions that you provided to the your entries and relationships in the validator are not deep copied.
        Returns:
        A copy of this validator with all its defined Validator.Entry and Validator.Relationship.

      • ifTrueThenCheck

        public static BiPredicate<Object,Object> ifTrueThenCheck(Predicate<Object> predicate)
        Returns a BiPredicate that checks to see if the first boolean argument implies the second Predicate. In other words, if the first argument is true and the second argument evaluates to false on the given Predicate, this check is false. Else, it is true.
        Parameters:
        predicate - The Predicate to test the second argument to the returned BiPredicate with.
        Returns:
        The created BiPredicate.

      • isImpliedBy

        public static BiPredicate<Object,Object> isImpliedBy(Predicate<Object> firstTest,
                                                     Predicate<Object> secondTest)
        Returns a BiPredicate that checks to see if the first Predicate implies the second. In other words, if the first one evaluates to true on the first object in the BiPredicate and the second evaluates to false on the second object, this check is false. Else, it is true. Analogous to isImplied(Object, Object).
        Parameters:
        firstTest - The first Predicate.
        secondTest - The second Predicate.
        Returns:
        The created BiPredicate.
